    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div type="letter">
                <div type="text">
                    <opener>
                        <placeName>13. Sea Houses | Eastbourne</placeName>
                        <date>July 30<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>.</date>
                        <salute>Dear Owen</salute>
                    </opener>
                    <div type="transcription">
                        <p>Capt. Sulivan’s address is simply “Guildford”: if the Memoir be too heavy for the Post, it c<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. be sent, no doubt, per S. W. Railway.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> With respect to the copy, you are so kind as to offer me, will you be so good as to have it left either at the Athenæum Club or Geological Soc<hi rend="superscript">y</hi>.—</p>
                        <p>We have been staying here with all our children for the last 2 or 3 weeks, but shall return home in a few days. The weather has been much against enjoying the sea.—</p>
                        <p>Your’s very truly | C. Darwin</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">1.00 S. W.] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi></note>
            </div>
                
                
            </div>
           
           
           <div type="footnotes">
                <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the address; CD and his family stayed at Eastbourne in July 1853 (see <hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 5).</note>
               <note xml:id="foot.f2">The memoir was presumably Owen’s ‘Description of some species of the extinct genus <hi rend="italic">Nesodon</hi>’ (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6084.xml">Owen 1853a</ref>). <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4614.xml">Bartholomew James Sulivan</ref> had collected the fossil remains of <hi rend="italic">Nesodon</hi> discussed by Owen at the Gallegos river in Argentina in 1845 (see <hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 3, letters from B. J. Sulivan, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-730.xml">13 January – 12 February 1845</ref> and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-886.xml">4 July 1845</ref>, and <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_903.xml">Brinkman 2003</ref>).</note>
            </div>
        
